{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c7207f6a-a302-4ef9-a7d4-91b33605a617","content":"Yes, both are known MSTest v4 breaking changes. Here's what's happening:\n\n## 1. Lost Test History in Azure DevOps\n\nMSTest v4 changed the default **test ID generation strategy**. The new IDs don't match your v3 IDs, so ADO treats every test as new.\n\n**Fix** — restore the legacy strategy in your `.runsettings`:\n\n```xml\n<MSTest>\n  <TestIdGenerationStrategy>DisplayName</TestIdGenerationStrategy>\n</MSTest>\n```\n\n## 2. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`\n\nIn v4, the `TestContext` passed to `ClassInitialize` is now a **class-level context**. Test-specific properties like `TestName` throw `InvalidOperationException` because no single test is associated with that phase.\n\n**Fix** for your code — remove the `TestName` access from `ClassInit`:\n\n```csharp\n[ClassInitialize]\npublic static void ClassInit(TestContext context)\n{\n    // context.TestName is not available here in v4\n    // Use context.FullyQualifiedTestClassName instead, or\n    // move per-test logic to [TestInitialize]\n}\n```\n\n## Other v4 Breaking Changes to Watch For\n\n| Area | Change |\n|------|--------|\n| **Parallel execution** | Now enabled by default; tests must be thread-safe |\n| **Timeout default** | Method-level timeouts now use `CooperativeCancellation` by default |\n| **`[DataRow(null)]`** | First arg `null` is ambiguous; use `[DataRow((object?)null)]` |\n| **Removed obsolete APIs** | Several long-deprecated members were removed |\n| **Assert.AreEqual on doubles** | Stricter floating-point tolerance enforcement |\n| **TestContext.Properties** | No longer writable in some contexts |\n\nWould you like me to update your `SetupTests.cs` to be v4-compatible?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"63e53e53-1196-44db-844e-d9f5ca098bd3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user has MSTest v4 and is encountering two specific issues. Let me provide a comprehensive answer about MSTest v4 breaking changes based on my knowledge:\n\n1. **Test ID changes (lost history in Azure DevOps)**: MSTest v4 changed the default test ID generation strategy. In v3, the default was `TestIdGenerationStrategy.FullyQualified` but in v4 it may have changed, or more specifically, MSTest v3.x introduced a new ID generation strategy and v4 made it the default. This causes Azure DevOps to see tests as new because their IDs changed.\n\n\n2. **TestContext.TestName in [ClassInitialize]**: The `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` methods is class-level rather than test-level, so accessing `TestName` throws an `InvalidOperationException` since the method runs once per class without a specific test context.\n\nThe main breaking changes in MSTest v4 are test ID generation shifting from the legacy hash format to fully qualified names by default, which breaks Azure DevOps test history, the removal of test-specific properties like `TestName` from class-level contexts, deprecated API removals, and changes to default timeout and parallelism behaviors. I'm realizing the test ID change is more nuanced—v3 used `Legacy` as the default strategy, v3.x added `FullyQualified` as an option, and v4 switched the default to `FullyQualified`, fundamentally altering how tests are identified.\n\nTo preserve ADO history, you can configure the runsettings to use `DisplayName` as the test ID generation strategy or apply the assembly-level attribute to revert to the older approach. For the `TestContext.TestName` issue in `ClassInitialize`, the context is now explicitly class-scoped, so accessing test-specific properties throws an exception—the workaround is simply not accessing `TestName` there since it was unreliable in that scope anyway. There are also other breaking changes like `DataRow` no longer accepting `null` directly as the first argument.","outputTokens":1216,"requestId":"BC28:26D998:22130E3:25F5F4A:69FAAAFD"},"id":"4d3d81d3-9a4d-4d6e-82da-5cb9e292c60b","timestamp":"2026-05-06T02:44:39.268Z","parentId":"a0deeb49-2c66-43e5-8cac-144bb56dc071"}
